ft announced that the GitHub Copilot Chat extension code will be open-sourced under the MIT license\n- The core functionality will be integrated into Visual Studio Code\n- **May 20**: GitHub launched a Copilot AI agent that can handle specific programming tasks, including checking and modifying code repositories\n\n**June 2025:**\n- **June 20**: GitHub announced that certain AI models (o1, GPT-4.5, o3-mini, and GPT-4o) will be deprecated starting July 2025, with recommended alternatives provided\n\n**August 2025:**\n- **August 8**: OpenAI released the GPT-5 series, which was simultaneously integrated into GitHub Copilot and other Microsoft platforms\n\n**Key 2025 Features:**\n- **Free version launched** with monthly limits (2,000 code completions and 50 chat requests)\n- **Multi-model support** allowing users to choose different AI models\n- **Copilot Edits** for multi-file editing experiences\n- **Custom instructions** functionality\n- Support for additional IDEs and languages\n\n---\n\n**Note:** The search results show updates throughout 2025, but if you're looking for specific changes that occurred exactly in February 2025, you may need to check GitHub's official blog or release notes for more detailed information from that specific timeframe.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
